{"id":"1609.06173","submitter":"Alexander Bilmes","authors":"Alexander Bilmes, Sebastian Zanker, Andreas Heimes, Michael Marthaler,\n  Gerd Sch\\\"on, Georg Weiss, Alexey V. Ustinov and J\\\"urgen Lisenfeld","title":"Electronic Decoherence of Two-Level Systems in a Josephson Junction","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. B 96, 064504 (2017)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevB.96.064504","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.mes-hall","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The sensitivity of superconducting qubits allows for spectroscopy and\ncoherence measurements on individual two-level systems present in the\ndisordered tunnel barrier of an $\\mathrm{Al/AlO_x/Al}$ Josephson junction. We\nreport experimental evidence for the decoherence of two-level systems by\nBogoliubov quasiparticles leaking into the insulating $\\mathrm{AlO_x}$ barrier.\nWe control the density of quasiparticles in the junction electrodes either by\nthe sample temperature or by injecting them using an on-chip dc-SQUID driven to\nits resistive state. The decoherence rates were measured by observing the\ntwo-level system's quantum state evolving under application of resonant\nmicrowave pulses and were found to increase linearly with quasiparticle\ndensity, in agreement with theory. This interaction with electronic states\nprovides a noise and decoherence mechanism that is relevant for various\nmicrofabricated devices such as qubits, single-electron transistors, and\nfield-effect transistors. The presented experiments also offer a possibility to\ndetermine the location of the probed two-level systems across the tunnel\nbarrier, providing clues about the fabrication step in which they emerge.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 14 Sep 2016 13:48:43 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 24 Jan 2017 09:03:22 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Thu, 17 Aug 2017 11:34:20 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-08-18"}
